[
    {
        "content": "<p>Morphisms of fibrations are usually taken to be commutative squares where the top horizontal arrow preserves cartesian arrows:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/rLctzY7ovAyKYIPHkqVIuY1I/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/rLctzY7ovAyKYIPHkqVIuY1I/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/rLctzY7ovAyKYIPHkqVIuY1I/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 264162437,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1638973802
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On the other hand, one could define morphisms of fibrations as follows:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/4rBIpuAGYDHobcTaBLaFc1dh/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/4rBIpuAGYDHobcTaBLaFc1dh/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/4rBIpuAGYDHobcTaBLaFc1dh/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 264162809,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1638973932
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I could expect the two definitions to be actually equivalent, but are they?</p>",
        "id": 264162892,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1638973973
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think this basically amounts to the fact that Fib is 2-fibered over Cat, and the fibers are Fib(X).</p>",
        "id": 264175073,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1638978679
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or, in lower-brow language, the universal property of pullbacks?</p>",
        "id": 264182834,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1638981797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/morphisms.20of.20fibrations/near/264162809\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>On the other hand, one could define morphisms of fibrations as follows:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/4rBIpuAGYDHobcTaBLaFc1dh/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>did you try to compute <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>F</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F^*{\\cal B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span></span>, just to see what you mean? if it is a strict pullback, then it is equivalent by the definition of pullbacks, but you are being evil looking for objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span> such thast <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Q</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Fx=Qb</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span>. if you want them to be isomorphic, then there are situations when coherence problems arise. (eg, take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\cal Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span></span> to be a group, and make sure that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> does not split...)) if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>F</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F^*{\\cal B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span></span></span> is a comma, then try to categorify the Hurewitz liftings, and you will see where grothendieck came from when he defined fibrations.</p>\n<p>but where did you get that square as a definition of fibration morphisms? even if we take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> to be the identity, the functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> may make the triangle commute, but may not preserve the cartesian liftings, and the fact that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> is a fibration is lost to it.</p>",
        "id": 264243303,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1639011315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assumed that he simply didn't write the condition of preserving cartesian arrows, since it's present in both versions of the definition.</p>",
        "id": 264243416,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1639011447
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And fortunately, the pullback <em>of a fibration</em> is also a bipullback, so there's no harm in being \"evil\" here.</p>",
        "id": 264243429,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1639011477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>sorrh, but that sounds like a bit of theology. strict pullbacks of functors are ok because they are also bipullbacks. does that bring the strict pullback of two functors into existence without comparing their object parts?</p>",
        "id": 264243811,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1639011800
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>((oops, it is 2am here. i'll check back.)) <span aria-label=\"sleeping\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f634\" role=\"img\" title=\"sleeping\">:sleeping:</span></p>",
        "id": 264243906,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1639011869
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The question (sorry if that's not explicit in the op) is indeed whether the 'upper' part of the second kind of morphisms automatically preserves cartesian arrows</p>",
        "id": 264322282,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1639065786
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"294557\">dusko</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/morphisms.20of.20fibrations/near/264243303\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>but where did you get that square as a definition of fibration morphisms? </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is what you get by Grothendieck construction of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>b</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Fib : Cat^{op} \\to Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ib</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> which sends a category X to the category Fib(X) of fibrations over it.<br>\nMaybe I can answer the question above myself: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> preserves cartesian arrows exactly if I ask morphisms in Fib(X) to preserve cartesian arrows</p>",
        "id": 264322633,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1639065899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is precisely what I was thinking with my sorta thoughtless answer.</p>",
        "id": 264359672,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1639080692
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, in both ways of phrasing the definition you have to explicitly require the functor to preserve cartesian arrows.</p>",
        "id": 264367371,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1639084533
    }
